SID: Cable modem gets primary SID during registration, and gets additional
     SIDs when different QoS flows start.
     SID is unique per DS (mac domain)

Service Flow ID: 32 bit ID unique per uBR10k box, for IOS SW to manage
     different service flow within the box.  Not visible outside the CMTS.

VCCI: Toaster's representation of IDB (HW and SW).
      HW IDB is for each physical interface.
      SW IDB is for each logical sub-interface (kind of like the reverse
      of cable bundling, where one sub-net consists of multiple physical
      interfaces.  Here, one physical interface contains multiple logical
      sub-interfaces).
      Say if one HW interface contains one sub-interface, there will be
      two VCCI assigned for Toaster.  Actual traffic will not flow thru
      HW interface.
      Typical sub-interface usage for Cable is VPN.


IP hash table and Mac hash table points to different objects, which will also
point to each other.  The SID table points to the first object created for the
CM/Host.

If a CPE host has static IP, then the object in IP hash table is created first.
If a CPE host gets its IP from DHCP, then the object in Mac hash table is
created first.
For CM, since it always use DHCP, its object in MAC table is created first.
     
